[2] Clinical manifestations - D614G mutation role?
Date: Mon 27 Jul 2020
From: Philip Tierno <germdoctor@gmail.com> [edited]


Unusual manifestations of SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-2) infection
--------------------------------------------------------
As I have been following the science and medical reports over these past few months of sequestration, I have been observing one report after another of unusual manifestations of SARS-CoV-2 (COVID-19) infections including in areas of the body far removed from the respiratory tract. Certainly, it is known that the virus causes respiratory and intestinal infections especially in individuals with co-morbidities like high blood pressure, diabetes, smokers (including vapor smokers), obesity, COPD, the elderly, and immunosuppressed.

We do know that the protein spike (S) on the surface of the virus attaches to ACE-2 receptors on human cells and likewise for animals. Previous studies have shown that ACE-2 proteins on alveolar epithelial cells in the lungs and on the enterocytes of small intestine serve as attachment sites for COVID-19 virus causing respiratory and intestinal infections. Yet we find many other manifestations of disease, some of which are strange, in this current pandemic caused by COVID-19 virus, such as clotting disease, infarcts, cardiovascular problems, inflammatory syndromes, nausea, and vomiting, persistent sporadic fever, chilblain, Kawasaki syndrome (toxic shock-like), headaches, brain fog, muscular fatigue, live, and kidney anomalies, etc. I think that these symptoms are not as unusual if one realizes that besides alveolar epithelial cells and enterocytes of the small intestine there are numerous other tissues that have the capacity for expressing the ACE-2 protein such as vascular endothelial tissue, renal tubular epithelia, Leydig cells in testes, lymph nodes, thymus, spleen, liver, skin, gastrointestinal tract, cerebral cortex, hypothalamus, brain stem and others. The prevalence of ACE-2 sites in such a wide variety of cell types may allow us to gain better insight and understanding into the pathogenesis of the COVID-19 virus infections.

Apparently the COVID-19 virus has a plethora of body sites to infect thereby causing additional pathology to primary respiratory pathology likely via a hematogenous route when the virus becomes systemic. The D614G mutation has also possibly enabled the spike protein to infect more cells and cell types than the non-mutated strains.

--
Dr Philip M Tierno, Jr
Professor, Microbiology and Pathology
NYU School of Medicine
NYU Langone Medical Center
New York, New York
USA
<germdoctor@gmail.com>
<Philip.Tierno@NYULangone.org>

[ProMED-mail would like to thank Dr Tierno for sharing his insights with us. The observation of multiple different organ involvement associated with infection with the SARS-CoV-2 infection is continually adding to the list of manifestations of the clinical presentation. Coincidentally, there was a lay press article in Forbes on 26 Jul 2020, mentioning hearing loss as the sole clinical manifestation of SARS-CoV-2 infection (see https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucelee/2020/07/26/can-covid-19-coronavirus-cause-hearing-problems-even-with-no-other-symptoms/#7e1afaaa1902. While the article has a whimsical presentation, the information provided is supportive of the observation).

Dr Tierno's provocative speculation re: the role of the D614G mutation in the affinity for more cell type infections sent us to the literature in search of studies addressing this observation. We found the articles suggesting the role in increasing the transmissibility of the virus (refs 1 and 2). In ref 3, the authors demonstrated susceptibility to infection with resultant high cellular transduction in lung, liver, and colon cells.

Again, Thank you Dr Tierno for sending your comments and raising the possibility of this mutation increasing the varied cell lines susceptible to viral transduction.

References
----------
1. Grubaugh ND, Hanage WP, Rasmussen AL. Making sense of mutation: what D614G means for the COVID-19 pandemic remains unclear [published online ahead of print, 2020 Jul 3]. Cell. 2020; S0092-8674(20)30817-5. doi:10.1016/j.cell.2020.06.040; https://www.cell.com/cell/pdf/S0092-8674(20)30817-5.pdf.
2. Korber B, Fischer WM, Gnanakaran S, et al. Tracking changes in SARS-CoV-2 spike: evidence that D614G increases infectivity of the COVID-19 virus [published online ahead of print, 2020 Jul 3]. Cell. 2020; S0092-8674(20)30820-5. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2020.06.043; https://www.cell.com/cell/pdf/S0092-8674(20)30820-5.pdf.
3. Daniloski Z, Guo X, Sanjana NE. The D614G mutation in SARS-CoV-2 spike increases transduction of multiple human cell types. Preprint. bioRxiv. 2020; 2020.06.14.151357. Published 2020 Jun 15. doi:10.1101/2020.06.14.151357 (https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2020.06.14.151357v2.full.
- Mod.MPP]

